The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 In a joint operation, the Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) and the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority (CMDA) on Sunday demolished 160 illegal structures over an 18.5-acre plot at Hatgachhia, off the Eastern Metropolitan Bypass. The plot will be developed as a permanent fair venue. 

 he operation was supervised by Javed Akhtar, additional district magistrate (land revenue) of South 24-Parganas; Tapas Chowdhury, sub-divisional officer (Alipore) and Soma Das, deputy superintendent of police (crime). They were accompanied by a large police contingent.

 senior district official said the documents produced by the squatters to prove that they had ?bought? the plot were found to be invalid. Each ousted person was given Rs 2,500 and an assurance of rehabilitation.

 Some of the water samples collected from the diarrhoea-affected areas of Behala have failed to comply with the prescribed standards. Mayor-in-council member (health) Pradip Ghosh said the sample that had the maximum contamination was collected from Satin Sen Pally. According to officer on special duty (health) Atanu Mukherjee, the civic body will run the four health camps in the area 0for a few more days. One person died and more than 100 people are affected by diarrhoea in the area. 

 A group of lawyers, including Colin Gonsalves and Jaymalya Bagchi, voiced their opposition to capital punishment at Press Club on Sunday. The lawyers argued that the state has no right to take away the life of a person who poses no threat from behind the prison bars. Gonsalves expressed the hope that a sustained campaign against death penalty would force the government to reconsider its stand. 

 A 25-member delegation of MLAs left for Delhi on Sunday evening. The members will meet Planning Commission deputy chairman Montek Singh Ahluwalia, railway minister Laloo Prasad Yadav, water resources minister Priya Ranjan Das Munshi, science and technology minister Kapil Sibal and surface transport minister TR Balu. Seven state ministers are part of the delegation. The Trinamul Congress has boycotted the trip.

 A delegation from Japan will meet health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra on Monday to discuss a development project to be undertaken at Infectious Diseases Hospital, in Beleghata. The state government has been eyeing a Rs 2-crore loan from Japan.

 Teachers and students of Calcutta University have appealed to vice-chancellor Asis Kumar Banerjee to fill up the posts of caretaker on the Rajabazar Science College, Alipore and Ballygunge Science College campuses. 

 The State Government Employees? Federation will move court if the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority (CMDA) refuses to accept its three-point charter of demand. Federation general secretary P.B. Nag said on Sunday the demands include implementation of the fourth Pay Commission?s recommendations on career advancement and publication of the report on an alleged misappropriation of the contributory provident fund.

 Three persons were detained in Salt Lake for violating building plans while constructing a retail outlet for a private telephone operator.

